<br>
First come first serve?  It works out really well to be honest with small camps and groups.  Things with a roughly 30 minute respawn rate.  However, those that usually "came first" are prepared.<br>
<br>
I guess it's sorta like the old Zordak fights.  Who has the right to the kill?  The cleric that has the weekend off and has been sitting there for two days, but doesn't have sufficient forces to kill him, or the cleric who showed up 2 hours ago when he got home from work with an army at his back?<br>
<br>
To be honest, due to recent events in the world of EQ, my opinion on this is heavily influenced.<br>
<br>
Verant has stated that nobody can 'claim' a camp.  If a mob is up, the first to pull wins.  They also ask out of common courtesy that if someone is camping something, you leave it alone.  <br>
<br>
It really honestly can't be fully dictated, since both are in the right.  Cleric A has been sitting there, but it's not his fault he has a lot of free time on his hand.  By the same measure, Cleric B has the numbers, it isn't his fault he has more friends at that time of day.<br>
<br>
It all comes down then to past occurences.  If Cleric A and B are old chums, one might back down for the other.  If they aren't however, shit may just hit the fan.<br>
<br>
<br>
Kill Stealing?  Whomever makes the first aggressive action other then proximity agro has the rights to the kill.<br>
<br>
Raid Stealing?  If there's one intended target, then it's a first pull first win situation.  Hence infamous "racing to targets" and all the bad blood that comes out of that.<br>
<br>
Camp stealing?  If you can hold the camp, kudos to you.  But if you don't have the class/numbers, or aren't pulling specific mobs, those that aren't being killed are up for grabs. <p><a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=35824><img src=http://www.theperfectflaw.com/picture/brain.gif></a><br>
